Someone in charge needs to see the below post from a patient in NY, Matthew Kabel. This needs to be addressed.I feel like I need to share what I've dealt with the last 14 days so everyone can understand why things are getting worse with COVID-19, something I may or may not have been battling for two weeks. I'll never know, and at this point I don't believe it matters anymore.Two weeks ago today I came down sick, for the next three days I had a low-grade fever (~100.6), dry cough and shortness of breath.No other symptOMS, which is exactly how COVID has been defined. I went to my Brooklyn doctor last Tuesday, and while in the waiting room I could hear the Nurse Practitioner saying how stupid the overreaction to COVID is. My doctor told me it probably wasn't COVID and sent me home on Tamiflu without actually testing me for the flu. Looking back, they totally blew me off and am sure others too. Strike one.I took Tamiflu for the 5 days and the fever went away, but my cough and shortness of breath persisted. We celebrated Thomas' Confirmation last Saturday under the assumption I had the flu but had finished the Tamiflu so was no longer contagious. By Monday I was consistently out of breath so was afraid my flu had transitioned to pneumonia. On Monday I went to the ER where both flu (via nasal swab) and pneumonia (xray) were RULED OUT. They took cultures (now known to be negative) and the doctor who had grown suddenly serious told me it "may or may not be COVID-19" but she could not test me as I was under 50 and had no known contact with somebody who either had it or left the country (yet I ride a filthy packed subway daily!). They had to save tests for those in distress who met criteria, her hands were tied.She weighed admitting me into isolation, but after discussing our medical experience with Sally and seeing that my bloodwork actually looked good we decided that I should go straight home and self quarantine on home treatment, which I did. However, she never did a Respiratory Viral Panel to rule out anything else, which looking back was a big mistake. Strike two.I stayed home in quarantine on treatment (steroids, 2 nebulizers, inhaler). We already know how to quarantine and be sanitary, this is the way we lived so much with Sally. The doctor said Nicole and the boys did not have to quarantine, just me. By Thursday we were anxious because the COVID fears got intense and people who knew I had been sick started asking about me, especially at William's school. Plus my breathing had not improved, which I never have respiratory issues. I worked with a politician friend to get into another ER to get a fresh set of eyes on me and have a full respiratory panel done so we could see if I had something else due to process of elimination to blame this on.Thursday was my 3rd MD visit and second hospital ER trip (different hospital). The doctor confirmed I was still wheezing despite 4 days of treatment (xray negative again) but again said he couldn't test me for COVID. He said, "They were supposed to release a bunch of new tests to us but never did." He said he was doing a full respiratory panel with a nasal swab so we could try to confirm something other than COVID, it'd test me for flu + at least 5 other things. My 2 hours in the ER on Thursday changed my perspective on everything...for the worse. It was overcrowded and they were grouping sick people with patients who were there with sprained wrists and the like. The guy next to me had flu confirmed while the woman across had back pain. There were a lot of people hacking, only half were wearing masks, and knew most would not actually be tested for COVID. Plus, the bathroom was filthy both times I used them so the cleaning crew could not keep up. I've spent enough time in hospitals to realize how very bad this was, the medical staff was exhausted and overwhelmed, COVID plus flu and everything else was going to spread fast, and and I wanted out of there. Finally the doctor sent me home to await results but said to quarantine for 14 days. When I told him I already was and asked from what period that should start, he looked at me exhausted and said, "14 days, that's all they're saying. It's all made up, it doesn't really mean anything because they don't know." That told me this was not under control.That night, I get a call from the covering doctor who said my flu and RSV tests were negative. I say "OK, but what about the other 4-5 COVID-19es they tested for?" Doctor said that's it, no other tests were ordered.They screwed up my tests. Strike three. All attempts to figure this out failed and I couldn't get the one test I actually needed. Last night I started to feel better and today I feel almost myself again outside of a nagging cough. It's been two weeks and nobody I've had contact with prior or during has been sick so have to believe I'm in the clear. I keep reading different opinions on how long it lives inside somebody, what I've realized is they have no idea. This could have been in the USA for weeks/months without them knowing. At this point it is what it is.I'm not here to point fingers, this was a failure on so many levels and there will be time for that later. For now, I hope everyone takes good care of themselves.I leave you with selfies from my three doctor visits. And I spent my birthday in isolation, so when this is over you better believe I'm doing a redo!

Therefore, garlic can definitely kill the COVID-19.What's the difference between a bacterial infection and a viral infection?BacteriaBacteria are single-celled microorganisms that thrive in many different types of environments. Some varieties live in extremes of cold or heat. Others make their home in people's intestines, where they help digest food. Most bacteria cause no harm to people, but there are exceptions.COVID-19esCOVID-19es are even smaller than bacteria and require living hosts � such as people, plants or animals � to multiply. Otherwise, they can't survive. When a COVID-19 enters your body, it invades some of your cells and takes over the cell machinery, redirecting it to produce the COVID-19.Allium Sativum (Allicin, Garlic, Garlic Extract)Studies reveal that garlic (it was later discovered that the compound Allicin that was largely responsible) is antibacterial, first noted in a study by Louis Pasteur in 1858, and Allicin is the substance in garlic which is responsible for the typical order. But there are dozens of compounds now known to be naturally inherent in garlic and some of which have certain medicinal value, including 33 sulfur compounds, 17 amino acids, germanium, calcium, copper, iron, potassium, magnesium, selenium, zinc, and vitamins A, B1 and C. Over the past 20 years, over 1,000 scientific publications have reported that garlic has demonstrated antibacterial, antifungal, antitumor, hypoglycemic, hypolipidemic and anti-atherosclerotic activities in both animals and humans. Garlic, when aged and powdered, can inhibit breast tumors in animals. Garlic contains 2 known anti-cancer compounds, selenium and germanium. Garlic has proven capable of reducing cholesterol and triglyceride levels even on unrestricted diets, while increasing HDL cholesterol (the good cholesterol) levels, and aids in the regulation of blood sugar levels.Garlic is thought effective in reducing blood pressure as well. Ajoene, a compound isolated from garlic in 1984, was found to demonstrate anti-thrombotic activity (preventing blood platelet aggregation or clotting of blood) or blood thinning activity, apparently by inhibiting exposure of fibrinogen receptors on platelet membranes. It was determined that ajoene is at least as potent as aspirin in this regard, and thus garlic appears to have some utility and value as a protective agent in atherosclerosis, COVID-19ry thrombosis and stroke. Garlic was also effective in increasing the natural killer-cell activity in AIDS patients, as well as improving other AIDS-related conditions including diarrhea, genital herpes, candidiasis and pansinusitis with recurrent fever.

My Friend work in Long Island Hospital Here is his heart broken message to CDC Please act NOW ??CDC recommending hospital staff use bandanas when masks run out. Hospitals are asking the public to sew masks. Here is a physician responding: Please don't tell me that in the richest country in the world in the 21st century, I'm supposed to work in a fictionalized Soviet-era disaster zone and fashion my own face mask out of cloth because other Americans hoard supplies for personal use and so-called leaders sit around in meetings hearing themselves talk. I ran to a bedside the other day to intubate a crashing, likely COVID, patient. Two respiratory therapists and two nurses were already at the bedside. That's 5 N95s masks, 5 gowns, 5 face shields and 10 gloves for one patient at one time. I saw probably 15-20 patients that shift, if we are going to start rationing supplies, what percentage should I wear precautions for?Make no mistake, the CDC is loosening these guidelines because our country is not prepared. Loosening guidelines increases healthcare workers' risk but the decision is done to allow us to keep working, not to keep us safe. It is done for the public benefit - so I can continue to work no matter the personal cost to me or my family (and my healthcare family). Sending healthcare workers to the front line asking them to cover their face with a bandana is akin to sending a soldier to the front line in a t-shirt and flip flops.I don't want talk. I don't want assurances. I want action. I want boxes of N95s piling up, donated from the people who hoarded them. I want non-clinical administrators in the hospital lining up in the ER asking if they can stock shelves to make sure that when I need to rush into a room, the drawer of PPE equipment I open isn't empty. I want them showing up in the ER asking "how can I help" instead of offering shallow "plans" conceived by someone who has spent far too long in an ivory tower and not long enough in the trenches. Maybe they should actually step foot in the trenches.I want billion-dollar companies like 3M halting all production of any product that isn't PPE to focus on PPE manufacturing. I want a company like Amazon, with its logistics mastery (it can drop a package to your door less than 24 hours after ordering it), halting its 2-day delivery of 12 reams of toilet paper to whoever is willing to pay the most in order to help get the available PPE supply distributed fast and efficiently in a manner that gets the necessary materials to my brothers and sisters in arms who need them.I want Proctor and Gamble, and the makers of other soaps and detergents, stepping up too. We need detergent to clean scrubs, hospital linens and gowns. We need disinfecting wipes to clean desk and computer surfaces. What about plastics manufacturers? Plastic gowns aren't some high-tech device, they are long shirts/smocks...made out of plastic. Get on it. Face shields are just clear plastic. Nitrile gloves? Yeah, they are pretty much just gloves...made from something that isn't apparently Latex. Let's go. Money talks in this country. Executive millionaires, why don't you spend a few bucks to buy back some of these masks from the hoarders, and drop them off at the nearest hospital.I love biotechnology and research but we need to divert viral culture media for COVID testing and research. We need biotechnology manufacturing ready and able to ramp up if and when treatments or vaccines are developed. Our Botox supply isn't critical, but our antibiotic supply is. We need to be able to make more plastic ET tubes, not more silicon breast implants.Let's see all that. Then we can all talk about how we played our part in this fight. Netflix and chill is not enough while my family, friends and colleagues are out there fighting. Our country won two world wars because the entire country mobilized. We out-produced and we out-manufactured while our soldiers out-fought the enemy. We need to do that again because make no mistake, we are at war, healthcare workers are your soldiers, and the war has just begun.God Bless
